  "prompt": "Which friends do you think are the best - school friends or college friends?",
  "response": "The question of whether school friends or college friends are the best is subjective and varies from person to person. Both types of friendships can be incredibly meaningful, but they often serve different purposes and play distinct roles in our lives.\n\n1. **School Friends**:\n   - **Shared History**: School friends often know you from a young age, witnessing your formative years and personal growth. This long-term bond can create a deep sense of trust and understanding.\n   - **Innocence and Simplicity**: Childhood friendships are often built on shared experiences, hobbies, and a carefree mindset, free from the pressures of adulthood.\n   - **Roots and Nostalgia**: They connect you to your roots and can provide a sense of continuity in your life.\n\n2. **College Friends**:\n   - **Shared Interests and Goals**: College friends often share similar academic interests, career aspirations, or life goals, which can create a strong intellectual and emotional connection.\n   - **Independence and Growth**: These friendships are forged during a time of personal independence and self-discovery, often leading to deeper, more mature bonds.\n   - **Networking and Support**: College friends can become part of your professional network and provide career-related advice and opportunities in the future.\n\n**Which is \"better\"?**\nIt really depends on your individual experiences and the quality of the friendships you've formed. Some people might cherish the lifelong closeness of school friends, while others might value the intellectual and emotional depth of college friendships. Ultimately, the best friends are those who support, understand, and uplift you, regardless of when or where you met them. Both types of friendships are valuable in their own ways, and many people are fortunate to have a mix of both in their lives.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
